[[Category:Trains]]

{{for|the 1995 film|Money Train}}
{{refimprove|date=October 2015}}
[[File:NY money train Oct 09.JPG|thumb|A money train car at the [[New York Transit Museum]]. The car was used by the [[New York City Subway]] until 2006.]]
[[File: NYCS Work Train Interior.jpg|thumb|Interior of the same car]]

A '''money train''' is one or more [[railcar]]s used to collect [[Fare control|fare collection]] revenue from stations on a [[Rapid transit|subway]] system and return it to a central location for processing. This train is typically used to carry [[money bag]]s guarded by [[transit police]] to deter robberies.

On the [[New York City Subway]], a “money train” was first mentioned in 1905, a year after the system opened.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Vandam |title=Cash and Carry |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/31/nyregion/thecity/31mone.html?ex=157680000&en=7f9eb6f4d0f34db4&ei=5124&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink |newspaper=New York Times |date=December 31, 2006 |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}</ref> Their trains were converted from subway cars that have been removed from service. This has since been discontinued, with the last service running in January 2006.<ref name=nyt /> Two of the cars went to the [[New York Transit Museum]] in Brooklyn.

The use of a train was necessary because of difficulties in getting to and from stations using over-street transport, and because, since the subway reaches every station, the rail system itself can be used to collect money from [[ticket machine]]s. The 1995 American [[crime]] thriller film ''[[Money Train]]'' depicts a robbery of such a train.

Singapore's [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] system introduced a four-car money train when the system was commissioned in 1987. Used to transfer cash trolleys from stations to a counting facility at Bishan Depot,<ref>{{cite web|title=Fare Payment Evolution: Interview|url=http://movingstories.smrt.com.sg/www/interview---tan-pang-chew.html|website=Moving Stories|publisher=SMRT|accessdate=7 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806192643/http://movingstories.smrt.com.sg/www/interview---tan-pang-chew.html|archive-date=6 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> the increased use of stored value tickets resulted in the train being decommissioned in 2007.

==Pay car==
{{main|Pay car}}
In Australia, the reverse procedure occurred with the [[New South Wales Government Railways]] fleet of '''pay buses'''. A small self powered railcar, they were used to deliver [[pay slip|pay packets]] containing cash to employees at remote railway stations, as well as maintenance gangs working on the tracks. This operation remained in service until the 1980s when it was supplanted by electronic payments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nswrailheritage.com.au/orhprojects/cashontrack/rail2paybus.htm |title=Ca$h On Track, The Story of the Rail Pay Bus |work=NSW Rail Heritage |publisher=www.nswrailheritage.com.au |accessdate=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208230004/http://www.nswrailheritage.com.au/orhprojects/cashontrack/rail2paybus.htm |archivedate=December 8, 2010 }}</ref>

