{{Other uses}} {{Redirect|Express rail|the railway in Hong Kong|Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link|the railway in Malaysia|Express Rail Link|the transloading network in the Port of New York and New Jersey|ExpressRail}} [[File:Acela old saybrook ct summer2011.jpg|thumb|An [[Amtrak]] [[Acela Express]] train]] [[File:Train animation (local and express).gif|thumb|The red trains are local, the blue trains are express]]
'''Express trains''' make a small number of stops, usually major destinations, allowing faster service than [[Local train|local trains]] that stop at most or all of the stations along their route.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/express%20train| title=express train| website=Merriam-Webster| accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/express-train| title=Definition of 'express train'| website=Collins English Dictionary| accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDIrAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA791&dq=express+train+definition&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjxwL7goYniAhUHna0KHcWbDy0Q6AEIXTAJ#v=onepage&q=express%20train%20definition&f=false| via=Google Books| page=791| title=Judicial and Statutory Definitions of Words and Phrases - Second Series| editor=the editorial staff of the National Reporter System| location=St. Paul, MN| publisher=West Publishing Co.| year=1914}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/subway/howto_sub.htm| title=How to Ride the Subway| website=MTA.info| accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref> They are sometimes referred to as "fast trains" (or an equivalent term, such as the German ''[[Schnellzug]]''), meaning that they are faster than other trains on the same route.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zU1NAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA767&dq=express+train+definition&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkoLLBponiAhUFTKwKHZBmApo4ChDoAQgxMAI#v=onepage&q=express%20train%20definition&f=false| via=Google Books| pages=767-768| title=Cases Decided in the Court of Session, Court of Justiciary, and House of Lords, From August 3, 1893, to August 25, 1894| volume=Fourth Series, Volume XXI| location=Edinburgh| publisher=T&T Clark, Law Booksellers| year=1894}}</ref> Though many [[high-speed rail]] services are express, not all express trains are "fast" relative to other services; early trains in the 19th-century United Kingdom were limited to {{convert|40|mph|km/h}}.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://archive.org/details/englishexpresst00foxwgoog| quote=express train definition.| page=[https://archive.org/details/englishexpresst00foxwgoog/page/n69 60]| via=Internet Archive| title=English Express Trains| first=E.| last=Foxwell| location=London| publisher=Edward Stanford| year=1884}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://archive.org/details/expresstrainsen00foxwgoog| quote=express train definition.| via=Internet Archive| page=[https://archive.org/details/expresstrainsen00foxwgoog/page/n103 93]| title=Express Trains, English and Foreign| first1=E.| last1=Foxwell| first2=T.C.| last2=Farrer| location=London| publisher=Smith, Elder & Co.| year=1889}}</ref> Express trains sometimes have higher fares than other routes, and bearers of a [[rail pass]] may be required to pay an extra fee. [[Travel class|First class]] may be the only one available.<!-- Commented out because it refers to a specific place and time and may not be relevant to all readers: In the United Kingdom, this practice was not codified in the parliamentary acts that created the early railway companies.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UnZbAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA10-PA30&dq=express+train+definition&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkoLLBponiAhUFTKwKHZBmApo4ChDoAQg3MAM#v=onepage&q=express%20train%20definition&f=false| via=Google Books| page=30| title=Report of the Commissioners of Railways| year=1848| location=London| publisher=W. Clowes & Sons}}</ref>--> Some express train routes that overlap with local train service may stop at stations near the tail ends of the line. This can be done, for example, where there is no supplemental local service to those stations. Express train routes may also become local when it is most practical to do so, such as during the night.
