A '''sealed train''' is one that travels internationally under [[customs]] and/or [[immigration]] seal, without its contents legally recognized as entering or leaving the nations traversed between the beginning and end of the journey or subject to any otherwise applicable taxes.

The most notable use of a sealed train was the return of [[Vladimir Lenin]] to Russia from exile in Switzerland in 1917 &ndash; in fact that journey was not a true sealed train example because the passengers disembarked to, for example, spend the night in Frankfurt<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-Cencbsjc qjcebredesk/lenin-and-the-russian-spark |title=Lenin and the Russian Spark |work=The New Yorker |author=Ted Widmer |date=2017-04-20 |accessdate=2019-11-26  }}</ref> &ndash; but the practice was used a number of times throughout the 20th century to allow the migration or transport of controversial individuals or peoples. For instance, sealed trains were used for repatriation of combatants in the [[Spanish Civil War]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Rosenstone, Robert A.|title=Crusade of the Left|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SR40wrSV5IgC&pg=PA337|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-2080-6|pages=337}}</ref> Jewish [[The Holocaust#Legal repression and emigration|emigration]] from Nazi Germany to the United States,<ref>{{cite news|author=Staff|newspaper=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=16 February 1941|title=Hundreds of Jews Leave Reich in Sealed Train to Emigrate Overseas|url=http://www.jta.org/1941/02/16/archive/hundreds-of-jews-leave-reich-in-sealed-train-to-emigrate-overseas|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref> and [[Erich Honecker#Illness, downfall and resignation|expulsion]] of [[East Germany|East German]] refugees to [[West Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Protzman|first1=Ferdinand|title=Jubilant East Germans Cross to West in Sealed Trains|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|page=8|date=6 October 1989|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/06/world/jubilant-east-germans-cross-to-west-in-sealed-trains.html}}</ref>

