{{short description|A non-invertible matrix}}
A '''singular matrix''' is a square matrix which is not [[Invertible matrix|invertible]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://mathworld.wolfram.com/SingularMatrix.html|title=Singular Matrix|last=Weisstein|first=Eric W.|website=mathworld.wolfram.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref> Alternatively, a matrix is singular if and only if it has a [[determinant]] of 0.<ref name=":0" /> When an <math>n\times n</math> matrix is taken to represent a [[Linear map|linear transformation]] in ''n''-dimensional [[N-dimensional Euclidean space|Euclidean space]], it is singular if and only if it maps any ''n''-dimensional hypervolume to a ''n''-dimensional hypervolume of zero volume.

