{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Francisco José de Goya y Lucientes - The sleep of reason produces monsters (No. 43), from Los Caprichos - Google Art Project.jpg | image_size=230px | title=The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters | other_language_1=Spanish | other_title_1=El sueño de la razón produce monstruos | artist=[[Francisco Goya]] | year=c. 1799 | type=[[Etching]], [[aquatint]], [[drypoint]] and [[Burin (engraving)|burin]] | height_metric=21.5 | width_metric=15 | height_imperial={{frac|8|7|16}} | width_imperial={{frac|5|7|8}} | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | museum= Various [[print room]]s have a print from the first edition. The one illustrated is at the [[Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art]].<ref name="Nelson">{{Cite web |url=https://art.nelson-atkins.org/objects/24528/the-sleep-of-reason-produces-monsters-no-43 |title=The sleep of reason produces monsters (No. 43)}} art.nelson-atkins.org.</ref> }}
'''''The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters''''' ({{lang-es|El sueño de la razón produce monstruos}}) is an [[etching]] by the Spanish painter and printmaker [[Francisco Goya]]. Created between 1797 and 1799 for the ''Diario de Madrid'',<ref name="Nehamas">{{cite journal |last1=Nehamas |first1=Alexander |title="The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters" |journal=Representations |date=2001 |volume=74 |issue=Spring}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eeweems.com/goya/sleep_of_reason.html |title=Goya - The Sleep of Reason |publisher=Eeweems.com |accessdate=2012-01-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107043903/http://eeweems.com/goya/sleep_of_reason.html |archivedate=2012-01-07 }}</ref> it is the 43rd of the 80 etchings making up the satirical ''[[Los caprichos|Los Caprichos]]''.<ref>[http://museum.cornell.edu/collections/view/the-sleep-of-reason-produces-monsters.html ''The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters''] [[Johnson Museum of Art]], [[Cornell University]], 2013. Retrieved 11 May 2013.</ref>
Many suggest that the artist Goya depicts himself asleep amidst his drawing tools, his reason dulled by slumber, bedeviled by creatures that prowl in the dark. The work includes owls that may be symbols of folly and bats symbolizing ignorance. Implied in Goya's preparatory inscription,<ref name="Nehamas">{{cite journal |last1=Nehamas |first1=Alexander |title="The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters" |journal=Representations |date=2001 |volume=74 |issue=Spring}}</ref> the artist's nightmare reflects his view of Spanish society, which he portrayed in the ''Caprichos'' as demented, corrupt, and ripe for ridicule.<ref>{{cite web | last = The Metropolitan Museum of Art | authorlink = Metropolitan Museum of Art | title = Francisco de Goya y Lucientes: The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters: Plate 43 of The Caprices (Los Caprichos) | url = http://www.metmuseum.org/TOAH/ho/09/eusi/ho_18.64.43.htm | accessdate = 2008-12-14}}</ref> The full epigraph for capricho No. 43 reads; "Fantasy abandoned by reason produces impossible monsters: united with her [reason], she [fantasy] is the mother of the arts and the origin of their marvels."<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jensen |first1=Robin M. |last2=Vrudny |first2=Kimberly J. |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=if4hQec2ClEC&pg=PA39 |title=Visual Theology: Forming and Transforming the Community Through the Arts |publisher=Liturgical Press |page=39 |isbn=978-0-814-65399-9}}</ref>
Occasionally the title phrase is rendered as "The dream of reason produces monsters", since the Spanish word "sueño" can mean either "sleep" or "dream".
Goya's etching, and its title, perhaps recalls the words of Teresa of Avila (1515-1582) "For since this humour [melancholy, ie. depression] can subdue reason, what won't our passions do once reason is darkened? ...if reason is wanting, madness results ..." ("The Book of her Foundations" [1573-6], 7, 2).
==Preparatory drawings== Goya produced preparatory drawings for all the prints in the "Los caprichos" series.<ref name="drawings">[https://www.museodelprado.es/en/whats-on/exhibition/solo-la-voluntad-me-sobra-drawings-by-goya/802339bb-1b74-8f92-d9ac-091244d4e474# Caprichos]. Goya. Drawings. "Only my Strength of Will Remains". Museo del Prado.</ref> One drawing suggests that ''The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters'' was being considered for use as the [[Book frontispiece|frontispiece]] of the collection, although in the event it was not used for this purpose in the printed version which starts with a self-portrait. <gallery> File:Prado - Los Caprichos - preparatory drawing - No. 43 - El sueño de la razon produce monstruos.jpg|1797 File:Ydioma universal.jpg|1797 </gallery>
==Technical aspects== As a set "Los caprichos" is notable for its use of [[aquatint]]. In ''The Sleep of Reason'' there is a contrast between the etched lines of the foreground and the areas of tone, produced by aquatint, which are used for the creatures in the background.
